        "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> Patch Set 3:\n> \n> As requested, I tested the nginx-svc-nodeport-ipv6.yaml blueprint in my environment and confirmed that 'concat' is being treated as a key, not an intrinsic function.  So it works.\n> \n> I still believe it's a bad idea to use 'concat' instead of a meaningful name for the parameter--it's confusing. The nginx-svc-nodeport-ipv6.yaml blueprint is actually unrealistic, since it hardcodes the port numbers.  In a real blueprint, the port numbers are likely to come from inputs, and that will lead to lines that mix 'concat' as a key and 'concat' as an intrinsic function:\n> \n> - concat: [{ concat: [{ get_input: [internalPort] },':', { get_input: [externalPort]} ]} ]\n> \n> It seems to me that the following is much clearer:\n> - port_mapping: [{ concat: [{ get_input: [internalPort] },':', { get_input: [externalPort]} ]} ]\n> \n> At the very least, if we going to keep this naming convention, we need really clear documentation explaining that concat is being used as a key, not an intrinsic function.  Anyone who is familiar with Cloudify blueprints but not familiar with the IPv6 feature in the k8splugin will be confused.\n\nCouldn't we just use:\n concat: [{ get_input: [internalPort] },':', { get_input: [externalPort]} ]\n\ninstead of:\n concat: [{ concat: [{ get_input: [internalPort] },':', { get_input: [externalPort]} ]} ]\n\n?\n\nI agree that it may be a bit confusing (using concat as key), but I'm not sure if the change is very urgent.",
